    "story": {
      "content": "Day 2, 4:45 AM. Most volunteers were still asleep. But not the Meditation Assists.\n\nSarah entered the ballroom in darkness. Meditation would begin at 6 AM. She'd be in position for the next three hours, watching 1,500 people drop into altered states. Ready to respond if someone needed help.\n\nShe'd trained for this. Read the protocol guide three times. Understood the difference between emotional release and crisis. Knew when to intervene and when to hold space. This was sacred responsibility.\n\nAcross the ballroom, the Room Reset team was already working. They'd been there since 10 PM the night before, after everyone left. Moving gravity chairs into position. Placing reserved signs. Setting up each section according to the detailed plan. Every chair in its place. Every sign correctly positioned.\n\nBy 5:30 AM, the Signs Lead was doing final checks. Walking each section, verifying placements, replacing damaged signs, ensuring clarity. The details that most people would never notice—but would definitely notice if they were wrong.\n\nOutside, the Coherence Healing Ballroom Lead was coordinating with venue staff. Setting up the flow for tomorrow's CH session. Positioning materials. Planning entry patterns. Making sure 100+ HealEEs could enter smoothly, be cared for properly, and exit safely.\n\nSection Leads were already in position by 5:45 AM, scanning their areas. Everything ready? Any issues? Medical access clear? Participants would arrive in 15 minutes.\n\nThese weren't the visible roles. No one thanked the Room Reset team for working until midnight. Participants didn't know Meditation Assists were watching during every meditation. The Signs Lead's work was invisible if done correctly.\n\nBut without these roles? Chaos.\n\nWithout Room Reset, participants would arrive to find gravity chairs in wrong places, signs missing, sections disorganized.\n\nWithout Meditation Assists, medical emergencies would go unnoticed until too late.\n\nWithout Signs Lead, confusion would ripple through seating, creating constant disruptions.\n\nWithout CH Coordinators, Coherence Healing would be logistical disaster instead of sacred experience.\n\nAfter the event, Sarah reflected: 'I used to think the important roles were the ones people saw—the Group Leads, the Door team, Customer Care. But now I understand: the most important roles are often the invisible ones. The ones that make everything else possible. The foundation no one notices—until it's not there.'"
