      "quote": "The difference between who you are and who you want to be is what you do.",
      "author": "Dr. Joe Dispenza",
      "content": "Additional Duties are the roles that support everything else. They're assigned ON TOP OF your primary Week Long role.\n\n**Why these roles exist:**\n\nYour primary role (Group Greeter, HST member, etc.) is your consistent responsibility throughout the week. But certain functions need specialists:\n\n• **Meditation Assist (MA):** Requires specific training and temperament. Watching hundreds of people in altered states, knowing when and how to intervene.\n\n• **Room Reset:** Happens after everyone leaves (late night). Requires physical work, attention to detail, coordination.\n\n• **Signs Lead:** Ongoing management of all signage throughout event. Requires organization and proactive problem-solving.\n\n• **Coherence Healing coordination:** Complex logistics that need dedicated focus during CH sessions.\n\n• **Section Leads:** Additional layer of section oversight and coordination.\n\nThese roles are typically assigned to experienced volunteers who can handle both their primary duty AND the additional responsibility.\n\n**Why this chapter matters:**\n\nEven if you're not assigned these roles your first event, you need to understand them:\n\n1. **Coordination:** Your primary role will interact with these roles. Group Greeters work with Room Reset. HST coordinates with CH Outside Ballroom Lead. Understanding their function helps you coordinate better.\n\n2. **Appreciation:** When you understand what these roles do, you appreciate the invisible work. The person who stayed until midnight setting up chairs deserves recognition.\n\n3. **Aspiration:** These are often roles experienced volunteers grow into. Understanding them helps you see the path forward.\n\n4. **Coverage:** Sometimes these roles need help. If you understand their function, you can support them effectively.\n\nThis chapter goes deep into:\n• Meditation Assist complete protocol and scenarios\n• Room Reset coordination with Signs and Greeters\n• CH Lead coordination (ballroom and outside ballroom)\n• Section Lead responsibilities\n• How these roles interconnect with primary duties\n\nThese are the roles that make the invisible visible through their absence. When they're done well, no one notices. When they're done poorly, everything suffers.\n\nLearn them. Respect them. Aspire to them."
    },
