      {
        "title": "Section Leads & Integration with Primary Roles",
        "content": "**SECTION LEADS:**\n\nAn additional layer of section oversight and coordination, typically assigned to experienced volunteers.\n\n**PRIMARY RESPONSIBILITIES:**\n\n**Section coordination:**. Support Group Lead with section management. Provide additional eyes and presence in section. Help monitor participant needs. Assist with flow and logistics during sessions. Coordinate with Group Greeters in section\n\n**Communication bridge:**. Relay information between Group Lead and other teams. Monitor Telegram for section-relevant updates. Communicate issues or needs to appropriate teams. Help Group Lead stay informed without being overwhelmed\n\n**Problem-solving:**. Handle minor section issues independently. Escalate complex issues to Group Lead. Support participants with questions or concerns. Ensure section runs smoothly\n\n**Backup leadership:**. Step in if Group Lead needs break or is handling another issue. Maintain section coherence and order. Keep team functioning smoothly\n\n**Why this role matters:**\n\n250 people in a section is a lot. Group Lead can't see everything or be everywhere. Section Lead provides additional oversight, support, and coordination.\n\n---\n\n**HOW ADDITIONAL DUTIES INTEGRATE WITH PRIMARY ROLES:**\n\n**Example: Group Greeter + Greeter/Room**. Day duties: Greet participants, help them find seats, create welcoming energy. Evening duties: Stay late to help Room Reset Lead set up gravity chairs and signs for your section. Integration: You know your section during the day, so you're perfect to set it up at night\n\n**Example: HST member + Meditation Assist**. Primary role: Support HSL with Coherence Healing logistics. Additional duty: Serve as MA during certain meditation sessions. Integration: When you're not in MA rotation, you're doing HST work. When you're MA, that's your focus.\n\n**Example: Group Lead + Section Lead**. Sometimes the same role. Sometimes Section Lead supports Group Lead as additional layer. Integration: Work together to manage section effectively\n\n**The principle:**\n\nAdditional Duties don't replace your primary role. They're assigned in addition to it, typically because:\n1. You have capacity and experience to handle both\n2. The timing doesn't conflict (Room Reset is evening, primary role is daytime)\n3. Your primary role complements the additional duty (Greeter who knows section does Room Reset for that section)\n\n**Managing dual responsibilities:**. Communicate clearly about your availability. Don't overcommit—if dual roles are too much, speak up. Prioritize based on timing (if both roles need you simultaneously, escalate to Team Lead). Take care of yourself—additional duties are demanding. Ask for support when needed\n\n**Recognition:**\n\nVolunteers who take on Additional Duties are providing extra service. This should be recognized and appreciated. If you see someone doing Room Reset at 10 PM after being in the ballroom since 5 AM—thank them. Their invisible work makes everything possible."
